    brief:'A 16-year-old, Sana, discloses (often indirectly \u2014 on the pretext of another problem) that she fears being taken abroad to be FORCED into marriage against her will. The task is the safeguarding consultation: recognise FORCED MARRIAGE as a form of ABUSE and a SAFEGUARDING/child-protection issue (and a criminal offence) \u2014 distinct from arranged marriage (which has consent); see her ALONE and respond with the "ONE-CHANCE RULE" (she may only get one chance to disclose \u2014 act sensitively and decisively, as she may not return); take the disclosure seriously, do NOT involve/contact the FAMILY or use family/community members as INTERPRETERS, and do NOT attempt mediation/family counselling (these can endanger her); assess RISK (imminent travel, threats, prior siblings forced, restriction of freedom) and safety, maintain CONFIDENTIALITY appropriately while recognising the safeguarding duty; FOLLOW LOCAL SAFEGUARDING procedures urgently \u2014 involve the safeguarding lead/children\u2019s social care, and signpost/contact the FORCED MARRIAGE UNIT (FMU) and relevant support; document carefully; and provide practical safety advice. The skill is recognising forced marriage, the one-chance rule, NOT involving family/mediation, urgent safeguarding referral and FMU. No NG12 cancer link.',
