    learning:'FORCED MARRIAGE (a marriage entered into without one or both parties\u2019 free and full CONSENT, involving coercion) is a form of ABUSE, a SAFEGUARDING/child-protection issue, and a criminal offence \u2014 distinct from an ARRANGED marriage, which both parties freely consent to \u2014 and a disclosure (often made indirectly under another pretext) must be taken extremely seriously. The critical principle is the "ONE-CHANCE RULE": the young person may have only one opportunity to disclose and seek help and may not present again (they could be taken abroad), so act sensitively but DECISIVELY at this consultation, seeing them ALONE. Essential safeguards: do NOT contact or involve the FAMILY, do NOT use family or community members as interpreters (use a professional interpreter), and do NOT attempt MEDIATION, family counselling or "talking to the parents" \u2014 these can place the person at serious risk (escalation, being taken abroad sooner, harm). Assess risk and safety (imminent travel plans and timing, threats/coercion, prior siblings forced, restriction of freedom), reassure them they have done the right thing, and follow local SAFEGUARDING procedures urgently \u2014 involving the safeguarding lead and children\u2019s social care (and police if imminent risk) \u2014 and signpost/contact the FORCED MARRIAGE UNIT and specialist support, maintaining confidentiality appropriately while acting on the safeguarding duty, documenting carefully, and giving practical safety advice (keeping documents/phone, emergency contacts, what to do if taken to an airport). The skill is recognising forced marriage, the one-chance rule, NOT involving family/mediation, and urgent safeguarding/FMU referral. No NICE NG12 cancer pathway applies.',
